-services/service/pnp/fsa/8b26000/8b26700/8b26745_150px.jpg#h=110&w=150", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/pnp/fsa/8b26000/8b26700/8b26745t.gif#h=111&w=150", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/pnp/fsa/8b26000/8b26700/8b26745r.jpg#h=469&w=640", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/pnp/fsa/8b26000/8b26700/8b26745v.jpg#h=750&w=1024"], "index": 4, "language": ["english"], "location": ["forrest county", "hattiesburg", "mississippi", "united states"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "image/jpg", "image/tif"], "number": ["http://www.loc.gov/item/fsa1998017639/pp", "2017758991", "http://www.loc.gov/item/19871415", "2017-08-09t10:25:01", "http://www.loc.gov/item/2017758991"], "online_format": ["image"], "original_format": ["photo, print, drawing"], "partof": ["lot 1631", "prints and photographs division", "farm security administration/office of war information black-and-white negatives", "prints & photographs online catalog (library of congress)", "american memory", "catalog"], "score": 42.677074, "shelf_id": "LC-USF34- 000514-D [P&P] LOT 1631 (corresponding photographic print)", "site": ["pictures", "catalog"], "subject": ["forrest county", "mississippi", "subsistence homesteads", "hattiesburg", "nitrate negatives", "united states"], "timestamp": "2022-04-25T17:50:25.385Z", "title": "New house at Hattiesburg, Mississippi", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2017758991/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/2016655401", "http://www.loc.gov/item/2016655401/", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0110", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0110/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0110_mv08/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0110_ms01/"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["bishop, john melville", "civil rights history project (u.s.)", "crosby, emilye", "dahmer, ellie j."], "date": "2015-01-01", "dates": ["2015"], "description": ["Ellie Dahmer discusses her involvement in the NAACP and voting rights activism in Forrest County, Mississippi. She recalls her experiences in education, both as a student at local schools, Alcorn State University, and Tennessee A&I, and as a teacher in schools throughout Mississippi. Her career as a Forrest County election commissioner is also discussed. She speaks about her husband, fellow activist Vernon Dahmer, and remembers the night when Klu Kulx Klan members burned her home, killing her husband and injuring her children."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2022-10-04T17:35:53.116Z", "group": ["afc2010039", "catalog-split-14", "catalog", "civil-rights-history-project", "main-catalog-split-14", "main-catalog"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/2016655401/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/afc/afc2010039/afc2010039_crhp0110/afc2010039_crhp0110_mv08.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/afc/afc2010039/afc2010039_crhp0110/afc2010039_crhp0110_ms01.gif#h=150&w=116"], "index": 5, "language": ["english"], "location": ["hattiesburg", "mississippi", "united states"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "application/pdf", "image/jpeg", "application/x-video"], "number": ["2020-01-23t09:39:29", "online resource", "2016655401"], "online_format": ["image", "pdf", "video"], "original_format": ["film, video"], "partof": ["american folklife center", "civil rights history project", "catalog"], "score": 34.297913, "shelf_id": "http://lccn.loc.gov/2016655401", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["mississippi southern college", "mississippi freedom project", "personal narratives", "interviews", "video recordings", "dahmer, ellie j.", "race relations", "hattiesburg", "african americans", "kennard, clyde", "voter registration", "dahmer, vernon ferdinand", "national association for the advancement of colored people", "mississippi", "ladner, joyce a", "ladner, dorie", "oral histories", "history", "ku klux klan (1915- )", "violence", "united states", "filmed interviews", "murder", "alcorn state university", "suffrage", "african american women civil rights workers", "civil rights movements", "african american women teachers", "hattiesburg (miss.)", "segregation in education"], "timestamp": "2022-10-17T14:38:46.135Z", "title": "Ellie Dahmer oral history interview conducted by Emilye Crosby in Hattiesburg, Mississippi, 2015 November 30", "type": ["moving image"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2016655401/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://lccn.loc.gov/2016655403", "http://www.loc.gov/item/2016655403/", "https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0112", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0112/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0112_mv07/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/afc2010039.afc2010039_crhp0112_ms01/"], "campaigns": [], "contributor": ["bishop, john melville", "branch, raylawni g.", "crosby, emilye", "smith, jeanette", "civil rights history project (u.s.)"], "date": "2015-01-01", "dates": ["2015"], "description": ["Raylawni G. Branch and Jeanette Smith discuss their involvement in the Hattiesburg, Mississippi-based Civil Rights Movement. They remember their upbringings as mixed race children, Smith in Mississippi and Branch in Mississippi and Chicago, Illinois. Branch recalls entering as one of the first black students at the University of Southern Mississippi. Both speak about their activism for voting rights and education, as well as sharing their philosophies on issues of race, discrimination, and activism."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2022-10-04T17:35:53.116Z", "group": ["afc2010039", "catalog-split-00", "catalog", "civil-rights-history-project", "main-catalog-split-00", "main-catalog"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/2016655403/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/afc/afc2010039/afc2010039_crhp0112/afc2010039_crhp0112_mv07.gif", "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/afc/afc2010039/afc2010039_crhp0112/afc2010039_crhp0112_ms01.gif#h=150&w=116"], "index": 6, "language": ["english"], "location": ["hattiesburg", "mississippi", "united states"], "mime_type": ["image/gif", "application/pdf", "image/jpeg", "application/x-video"], "number": ["2016655403", "online resource", "2020-02-20t15:36:11"], "online_format": ["image", "pdf", "video"], "original_format": ["film, video"], "partof": ["american folklife center", "civil rights history project", "catalog"], "score": 34.297913, "shelf_id": "http://lccn.loc.gov/2016655403", "site": ["catalog"], "subject": ["mississippi freedom project", "social justice", "personal narratives", "interviews", "medical committee for human rights (u.s.)", "video recordings", "washington, d.c.)", "race relations", "hattiesburg", "branch, raylawni g.", "carmichael, stokely", "african americans", "dahmer, vernon ferdinand", "school integration", "christianity", "deacons for defense and justice", "march on washington for jobs and freedom", "student nonviolent coordinating committee (u.s.)", "head start program (u.s.)", "national association for the advancement of colored people", "mississippi", "university of southern mississippi", "smith, jeanette", "religious aspects", "mccain, william d.", "william david)", "history", "oral histories", "council of federated organizations (u.s.)", "till, emmett", "united states", "filmed interviews", "suffrage", "african american women civil rights workers", "evers, charles", "civil rights movements", "hattiesburg (miss.)", "segregation in education"], "timestamp": "2022-10-17T14:38:46.135Z", "title": "Raylawni G. Branch and Jeanette Smith oral history interview conducted by Emilye Crosby in Hattiesburg, Mississippi, 2015 December 01", "type": ["moving image"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/2016655403/"}], "resource": {"fulltext_file": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.xml&format=alto_xml&full_text=1", "image": "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:msar:batch_msar_lapis_ver01:data:sn85044791:00383345066:1958061901:0434/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg", "pdf": "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.pdf", "segment_count": 4, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn85044791/1958-06-19/ed-1/", "word_coordinates": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service"}, "resources": [{"fulltext_file": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.xml&format=alto_xml&full_text=1", "image": "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:msar:batch_msar_lapis_ver01:data:sn85044791:00383345066:1958061901:0434/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg", "pdf": "https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.pdf", "segment_count": 4, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn85044791/1958-06-19/ed-1/", "word_coordinates": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service"}], "segment_id": "/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.xml", "segments": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn85044791/1958-06-19/ed-1/?sp=1"], "batch": ["msar_lapis_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/alabama/", "2/united states/alabama/baldwin/", "3/united states/alabama/baldwin/fairhope/", "1/united states/mississippi/", "2/united states/mississippi/forrest/", "3/united states/mississippi/forrest/petal/", "3/united states/mississippi/forrest/hattiesburg/"], "contributor": ["mississippi department of archives and history"], "date": "1958-06-19", "dates": ["1958-06-19"], "description": ["East Side By P D 3 The following was stolen from the San Francisco Chron icle and changed just enough to fit this locality St Peter faced two little old ladies who applied for admission at the Pearly Gates After asking all the pertinent questions about saying their prayers etc he asked one lady where she lived Cincinnati she said Okey you may go in And where are you from he asked the other lady Hattiesburg was the reply Well said St Peter you may go In but youre not going to like it No doubt youve heard the comment about the recession which has been attributed to Harry Truman in which he is to have said A recession is when the fellow next door is unemployed a depression is when youre unemployed Someone told me about the comment by some fellow suf fering from what most of us suffer from the folks next door Said the man You know everytime I catch up with that fellow Jones next door he refinances Then Robert Spivack the New York Post writer whose column Watch On The Potomac I carry told about the man who drove an old auto of some make"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2023-07-03T13:44:53.044Z", "group": ["ndnp/msar", "mississippi-department-of-archives-and-history"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn85044791/1958-06-19/ed-1/?sp=1", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:msar:batch_msar_lapis_ver01:data:sn85044791:00383345066:1958061901:0434/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg#h=449&w=301", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:msar:batch_msar_lapis_ver01:data:sn85044791:00383345066:1958061901:0434/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=899&w=602", "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.xml&format=alto_xml"], "index": 1, "language": ["english"], "location": ["forrest county", "mississippi", "fairhope", "baldwin county", "forrest", "hattiesburg", "alabama", "baldwin", "petal", "united states"], "location_city": ["fairhope", "petal", "hattiesbur